[7] Michigan, USA
Date: Fri 31 Jan 2020
Source: The Sault News [edited]
https://www.sooeveningnews.com/sports/20200131/flu-rates-on-rise-in-michigan


As the flu rates are beginning to rise dramatically, more public schools are shutting down for widespread illness. JKL Bahweting Elementary School closed last week from Tues 21 Jan to Fri 24 Jan [2020]. Now, Rudyard Area Schools recently announced that they are closed for the rest of this week and will not return until Monday [3 Feb 2020]. Brimley Schools were also closed this past Tuesday and Wednesday [28-29 Jan 2020] due to excessive absences from flu and fever.

According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), "Flu symptoms include fever, cough, sore throat, runny or stuffy nose, body aches, headache, chills, and fatigue. Some people also may have vomiting and diarrhea. People may be infected with flu and have respiratory symptoms without a fever."

According to the Michigan Flu Focus, a weekly influenza surveillance report as released by the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services (MDHHS), Michigan's influenza activity is considered to be widespread. This is considered the worst severity of influenza activity on the 5-tier scale. Michigan's influenza-like-illness (ILI) rate as of December was 1.2%. ILI is defined as fever (temperature of 100 deg F [37.8 deg C] or greater) and a cough and/or a sore throat without a known cause other than influenza, according to MDHHS. However, as of 18 Jan [2020], Michigan's ILI activity has nearly doubled at 2.2%.

There have been approximately 54 pediatric deaths due to influenza just in the 2019-2020 flu season. According to the report, 2 pediatric influenza B deaths have been confirmed by MDHHS this season alone.

"The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention have once again begun to release preliminary burden estimates for the 2019-2020 influenza season," said DHHS in the report. "From 1 Oct 2019 through 18 Jan 2020, it is estimated that there have been 15-21 million flu illnesses, 7-10 million flu medical visits, 140 000-250 000 flu hospitalizations, and 8200-20 000 flu deaths (in the United States)."

CDC recommends citizens take 3 necessary courses of action when it comes to avoiding and limiting their exposure to influenza:

1st, "get the flu vaccine. It is considered the most important step in protecting against flu viruses. Everyone 6 months of age and older should get a flu vaccine every year before flu activity begins in their community, before the end of October. Those most at risk for serious flu complications are young children, pregnant women, people with serious health conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, or heart and lung disease), and people 65 years and older."

2nd, "take preventative actions to stop the spread of germs. Clean and disinfected surfaces and objects that may be contaminated with germs like the flu. If you are sick with flu symptoms, CDC recommends that you stay home for at least 24 hours after your fever is gone except to get medical care or for other necessities (your fever should be gone for 24 hours without the use of a fever-reducing medicine). Cover your mouth and nose when you cough or sneeze and avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth."

Finally, "take flu antiviral drugs appropriately if your doctor prescribes them. Antiviral drugs are different from antibiotics. They are prescription medicines (pills, liquid, or an inhaled powder) and are not available over the counter. Studies show that flu antiviral drugs work best for treatment when they are started within 2 days of getting sick, but starting them later can still be helpful, especially if the sick person has a high-risk factor or is very sick from flu. Follow your doctor's instructions for taking this drug."

However, the flu is not the only illness Americans have been concerned about. As of 21 Jan [2020], there was a confirmed case of 2019 novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV). Since then, there have been 4 additional positive cases as of 27 Jan [2020] [for a total of 5 cases in the US]: one in Arizona, 2 in California, one in Washington state, and one in Illinois. No known cases have been reported in Michigan.

This respiratory illness was 1st identified in Wuhan, China. The cause of origin was originally anticipated to be an animal-to-person spread due to China's large seafood and animal market. However, recent patients have not had exposure to animal markets, suggesting that this is a person-to-person spread. Symptoms can include fever, cough, and shortness of breath and may appear 2-14 days after exposure. Because this virus is new, it is still being closely monitored and investigated by CDC.

[byline: Taylor R. Worsham]

